Taking vitamin D supplements and getting some sun exposure daily can lower the risk of breast and colorectal cancers.
Studies show that higher vitamin D levels reduce breast cancer risk by half and colorectal cancer risk by two-thirds.
Research analyzed data from 1,760 individuals for breast cancer and 1,448 for colorectal cancer.
Increasing vitamin D levels to 34 ng/ml could cut colorectal cancer rates in half.
Experts recommend 1,000 IUs daily to reduce cancer risk safely.
Sunlight, diet, and supplements are sources of vitamin D, crucial for cancer prevention.
Adequate vitamin D levels could prevent 600,000 cancer cases annually
